Poor people are pushed out of the benefits system and the electoral process through burdensome paperwork for the same reason: the State is elitist and wants them kept from participating by any means.

It’s easy enough to run when you can pay someone to file your shit properly and on time for you. But good luck if you’re trying to figure out what to do on the SoS’ trash ux/ui website written in pseudo-legalese, or by calling agencies that all give you different answers.

People who run for office while juggling kids and low pay and housing insecurity and financial insecurity are overcoming huge barriers that aren’t even bumps in the road for candidates with money, lawyers, and institutional backing.

If I want to e-file the regular, required accounting paperwork, an application has to be faxed to the state and then a response has to be faxed back. This has legit tripped me up. Some people don’t have reliable internet access, and CA is using obsolete 90s tech.

But I have a full time job and experience in: • electoral organizing • business management/entrepreneurship • marketing • accounting • film production • graphic design • web design • hell, even hair and makeup and all of that affords me only a semi-credible campaign.

Part of the reason I’m running for AD15 is to get firsthand experience with the process of being a candidate - cuz, ya know, “If you know want to change things, run for office!” is the line we’re fed.
It’s not just benefits programs that are so burdened with paperwork that poor folks are practically precluded from participating, it’s the electoral system too.
So that’s my long-winded way of saying, “Ehhhhhh ...” re: AB5. Workers’ security first. That’s my priority. I can’t tell yet if that’s what AB5 accomplishes.

I do think that people, orgs, and industries that are invested in the status quo rely on fear mongering to achieve their political agendas, so I want to step back from speculative worry and see how things shake out. Especially since AB5 is in effect until November at least.

AB5 hasn’t even been in effect for a month. To have a solid opinion, I need to know how it’s actually affecting ICs: whether their clients or income streams have dried up, whether they’re receiving benefits, the differences between industries and job types, attrition rates ...
It’s good that they’re trying to go after exploitative labor practices, but like nearly every bill that comes out of the legislature that attempts to tackle big problems, it’s a mess.
The ultimate problem that AB5 is trying to address is that businesses and clients can’t be relied upon to pay workers commensurate with their labor, let alone cost of living expenses.
Protections for sex workers? Yaaay. The fact that some but not other creative workers are exempt? What it’s already done to journalism in the state? Fffffffffff-
Ultimately that’s what I want for everyone: enough material stability that we can take care of basic needs and societally imposed expenses. Does AB5 do that? ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

Here’s my unsatisfying thoughts on AB5: I’m agnostic. I work in film production, so I’ve been an independent contractor before. Currently I’m full time, and the material difference between being FT or IC is huge. I can reliably save, pay my student loans, pay bills on time ...
